<!-- MSS. Eur. C. 214
Synoptic text of MSS. London, SOAS 41394, reverse, and India Office Library, no nr., observe. [now MSS Malay A.2] by Dr. P. Voorhoeve
Both MSS. are written on tree bark in rèntjong characters. The SOAS MS. is from the Marsden collection; the provenance of the India Office MS. is not known, but it may have about the same age.
The following text is not a critical edition; it simply registers all the variant readings of the two MSS. Where I preferred one reading I have put this is in the text and the other one in the note, but in many cases I have chosen at random.
A = MS. SOAS.
B = MS. India Office. [MSS Malay A. 2]
(  ) = not in A; (h) = has ‘, B has h; (V) = A has a, B has vowel.
‘  ’ not in B; ‘h’ = B has ‘, A has h ; ‘V’ = B has a, A has vowel.
“  ” = illegible in B.
!  ! : the following note number refers to all the words between the enclamation-marks.
 C = the text printed in De talen en letterkunde van Midden-Sumatra, by A.L. van Hasselt. Leiden 1881, p.11-13. It reproduces very imperfectly a text written on five flat strips of bamboo. I have tried in vain to find the original. It once belonged to Mr. van Schouw Santvoort, to whom it had been presented by Dr. H.M.D.van Riemsdijk (c. 1877). Between an initial and a final passage not found in A and B this text consists of a number of sentences that are also found in A and B, but in a different order. Together they represent about one quarter of the text of A and B. If we number the corresponding passages 1-23 in the order in which they are found in A and B, and call C’s intervening sentences that I have not identified in A and B. O, the order of the text in C is: 1 – 2 – 18 – 0 – 22 – 23 – 0 – 9 – 5 – 10 – 7 – 13 – 15 – 0 – 16 – 1a – 17 – 8 – 0 – 14 – 0 – 4 – 6 – 0 – 3 – 16 – 0 – 20 – 23 – 0 – 11 – 12 – 19 – 20 – 21 –
C is still more corrupt than A and B.
The spelling of C is influenced by Redjang pronunciation, e.g. asa = asal, Redjang asea.
2 / indicates the beginning of a page in A; 2 / in B.
The text is an allegorical poem in which life is compared to a voyage in a ship. The parts of the ship are given Arabic names, just as in the Sja’ir Perahu (Doorenbos’s edition of Hamzah Fansuri p. 16-19), but all the names are different.
Many sentences in our text have the form of lines of a sja’ir, and many of these lines rhyme, but not always in groups of four. The suffix –nja is left out of consideration for the rhyme in such lines as:
tawakal akilum nama gegadingnja
(the following lines rhyme in –ing).
Is seems probable to me that the text originally was a sja’ir and that it got its present corrupt form in the course of literary, and perhaps oral, tradition. Some words that disturb the rhythm look like glosses.
Hamzah’s vocabulary has influenced our author; he even uses the word bapai, Hamzah’s peculiar form for bapa, father. In his ideas the author follows the system of the seven grades, which became known in Indonesia in the 17th century.
In the colophon of C the text is called surat tabaris. With some audacity one might suppose this to mean that its authorship is ascribed to Sjamsi Tabrīz. However this may be, the copyist held it in great awe. He says that losing the manuscript would be an unforgivable sin and would be punished by a sojourn in the fire of hell. -->

